<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fairmaire" authorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pristonychus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pristonychus alticola" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Pristonychus alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fairmaire, 1889 (type locality: Mountain Yeomatong, North Myanmar; holotype in NZSI), by monotypy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
Among the seven genera of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pristonychus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Dolichina">Dolichina</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andrewes" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xestopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xestopus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Xestopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from others by the following character combination: third antennomere very long, usually longer than the first two antennomeres combined; tooth of mentum bifid; pronotum more or less cordiform; elytra with microsculpture nearly isodiametric, parascutellar seta present, elytral disc without setigerous pores; lateral grooves absent on metatarsomeres I-IV; males with right paramere hooked at apex; female apical gonocoxite with one ensiform seta at external margin (in most specimens) and sensory pit absent. Detailed descriptions and a key to the genera in the subtribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andrewes" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xestopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Dolichina">Dolichina</taxonomicName>
have been provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Casale, A" journalOrPublisher="Senckenbergiana Biologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="383 - 395" refId="B2" refString="Casale, A, 1981. Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera). Senckenbergiana Biologica 61 (1980): 383 - 395" title="Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera)." volume="61" year="1981">Casale (1981)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Sciaky, R" journalOrPublisher="Bolletino della Societa Entomologica Italiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="221 - 232" refId="B17" refString="Sciaky, R, Wrase, DW, 1998. Two new genera of Sphodrini Dolichina from China (Coleoptera Carabidae). Bolletino della Societa Entomologica Italiana 130: 221 - 232" title="Two new genera of Sphodrini Dolichina from China (Coleoptera Carabidae)." volume="130" year="1998">Sciaky and Wrase (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Comparisons.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
This genus is most similar to the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Dolichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dolichus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Dolichus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bonelli, sharing the large body size (&gt;15 mm), but its members differ from those of the latter in having the tooth of the mentum bifid, the pronotum cordiform, elytral interval 3 without setigerous pores, and the right paramere of male genitalia apically hooked.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">This genus includes eight species distributed along the Himalayas (two in Nepal, three in Bhutan, two in China, and one in Myanmar).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="139" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
The type species of this genus, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xestopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xestopus alticola" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Xestopus alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fairmaire, 1889) was described from Mount Yeomatong, northern Myanmar. In the two versions of the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
Catalogue of Palearctic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andrewes" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xestopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hovorka, O" editor="Loebl, I" journalOrPublisher="1). Archostemata-Myxophaga-Adephaga. Apollo Books, Stenstrup" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="529 - 530" refId="B8" refString="Hovorka, O, Sciaky, R, 2003. Subtribe Dolichina Brulle, 1834. In: Loebl, I, Smetana, A, Eds., Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol. 1). Archostemata-Myxophaga-Adephaga. Apollo Books, Stenstrup: 529 - 530" title="Subtribe Dolichina Brulle, 1834." volumeTitle="Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol." year="2003">Hovorka and Sciaky 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hovorka, O" editor="Loebl, I" journalOrPublisher="1. 2 nd Edn.). Brill, Leiden and Boston" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="768 - 769" refId="B7" refString="Hovorka, O, 2017. Subtribe Dolichina Brulle, 1834. In: Loebl, I, Loebl, D, Eds., Catalogue of Palearctic Coleoptera (Vol. 1. 2nd Edn.). Brill, Leiden and Boston: 768 - 769" title="Subtribe Dolichina Brulle, 1834." volumeTitle="Catalogue of Palearctic Coleoptera (Vol." year="2017">Hovorka 2017</bibRefCitation>
), the distribution of this species includes Sichuan and Sikkim and both these two are doubtful. The record for Sikkim was added by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1937.tb00297.x" author="Andrewes, HE" journalOrPublisher="The Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London (B)" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="59 - 63" refId="B1" refString="Andrewes, HE, 1937. Keys to some Indian genera of Carabidae (Col.). VIII. The genera of the Sphodrini group. The Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London (B) 6: 59 - 63, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1937.tb00297.x" title="Keys to some Indian genera of Carabidae (Col.). VIII. The genera of the Sphodrini group." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1937.tb00297.x" volume="6" year="1937">Andrewes (1937)</bibRefCitation>
; however, this locality and the type locality are extremely distant from each other for a species with apterous members. In addition, the record for Sikkim maybe a different species (
<bibRefCitation author="Morvan, P" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="31 - 42" refId="B12" refString="Morvan, P, 1979. Ergebnisse der Bhutan-Expedition 1972 des Naturhistorischen Museums in Basel. Coleoptera: Fam. Carabidae, tribus Sphodrini. Entomologica Basiliensia 4: 31 - 42" title="Ergebnisse der Bhutan-Expedition 1972 des Naturhistorischen Museums in Basel. Coleoptera: Fam. Carabidae, tribus Sphodrini." volume="4" year="1979">Morvan 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Casale, A" journalOrPublisher="Senckenbergiana Biologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="383 - 395" refId="B2" refString="Casale, A, 1981. Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera). Senckenbergiana Biologica 61 (1980): 383 - 395" title="Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera)." volume="61" year="1981">Casale 1981</bibRefCitation>
). No other literature records have reported 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. alticola" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="alticola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">X. alticola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Sichuan, and, in fact, no 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andrewes" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xestopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xestopus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">Xestopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens have been found in that province during our many expeditions in Sichuan, so we also doubt the reliability of this distributional record.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="139">
<bibRefCitation author="Casale, A" journalOrPublisher="Senckenbergiana Biologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" pagination="383 - 395" refId="B2" refString="Casale, A, 1981. Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera). Senckenbergiana Biologica 61 (1980): 383 - 395" title="Carabidae dell'Himalaya Nepalese. Sphodrini nuovi o poco noti (Insecta: Coleoptera)." volume="61" year="1981">Casale (1981)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that the three species from Bhutan (
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. walteri" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="walteri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">X. walteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Morvan, 1978), 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. bhutanensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="bhutanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">X. bhutanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Morvan, 1979), and 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. cordicollis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="cordicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">X. cordicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Morvan, 1979)) may represent three subspecies of a single species or eventually be combined into one species when abundant materials are available. Conversely, the male allotype and female holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. nepalensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="139" rank="species" species="nepalensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="139">X. nepalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably represent two different species, in our opinion, based on the original description and figures. The male differs from the female in having elytra with (1) rufous color in the scutellar region and along the sutural margin to mid-length, (2) the humeri more rounded, (3) the basal margination markedly sinuate, and (4) the apices more rounded and slightly oblique medially. Thus, a revision appears necessary to deal with this situation.
</paragraph>
